      <data key="d0">JUDICIAL MAGISTRATE</data>
      <data key="d1">PERSON</data>
      <data key="d2">25.0</data>
      <data key="d5">The Judicial Magistrate is a type of magistrate with specific responsibilities and jurisdiction within the legal system. According to the provided descriptions, the key roles and responsibilities of a Judicial Magistrate include:

1. Handling cases related to bail: Judicial Magistrates have the authority to handle cases involving bail, which is the release of an accused person from custody upon the provision of security to ensure their appearance in court for trial.

2. Arresting or ordering the arrest of an accused person: If an offense is committed in the presence of a Judicial Magistrate within their local jurisdiction, they have the power to arrest the accused or order their arrest.

3. Presiding over courts established under the BNSS: Judicial Magistrates of the first and second class are appointed to preside over the courts established under the Bangladesh National Shipping Corporation (BNSS) Act.

The descriptions indicate that Judicial Magistrates play a crucial role in the criminal justice system, with the authority to handle bail-related cases, make arrests, and preside over specialized courts. Their jurisdiction is limited to their local area, and they are responsible for ensuring the proper administration of justice within their purview.

It is important to note that the provided descriptions do not contain any contradictory information, and the summary presented above is a comprehensive representation of the key roles and responsibilities of a Judicial Magistrate based on the given data.</data>
