      <data key="d0">CHIEF JUDICIAL MAGISTRATE</data>
      <data key="d1">PERSON</data>
      <data key="d2">25.0</data>
      <data key="d5">The Chief Judicial Magistrate is a senior judicial officer who holds a significant position in the Indian legal system. This role is responsible for overseeing and presiding over a variety of legal proceedings and cases within their jurisdiction.

The primary responsibilities of the Chief Judicial Magistrate include hearing and adjudicating criminal cases, as well as considering bail applications for non-bailable offences under the Bail and Bonds Act (BNSS). They have the authority to impose sentences and pass judgments on these matters, playing a crucial role in the administration of justice.

In addition to their core judicial duties, the Chief Judicial Magistrate may also be conferred with additional powers by the High Court. These supplementary powers can vary depending on the specific jurisdiction and the needs of the legal system in that region. This flexibility allows the Chief Judicial Magistrate to adapt their role and responsibilities to better serve the local community and address the unique challenges they may face.

The Chief Judicial Magistrate is a senior-level position within the judicial hierarchy, commanding respect and authority within the legal community. They are tasked with upholding the rule of law, ensuring fair and impartial proceedings, and safeguarding the rights of all individuals who come before their court.

Through their diligent efforts and commitment to justice, the Chief Judicial Magistrate plays a vital role in maintaining the integrity of the Indian legal system and promoting the principles of fairness, equality, and the protection of individual rights. Their decisions and rulings can have significant impacts on the lives of those involved, underscoring the importance of their role and the need for a highly qualified and experienced individual to fill this position.</data>
