      <data key="d0">INDIAN PENAL CODE, 1860</data>
      <data key="d1">ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d2">32.0</data>
      <data key="d5">The Indian Penal Code, 1860 (IPC) is the primary criminal code of India, which serves as the substantive criminal law in the country. It was enacted in 1860 during the British rule and has since been the foundation of the criminal justice system in India.

The IPC defines various offenses and their corresponding punishments, covering a wide range of criminal activities, including murder, theft, assault, and fraud, among others. It provides a comprehensive legal framework for the administration of criminal justice in India, with the Code of Criminal Procedure (CrPC) outlining the procedures for implementing the provisions of the IPC.

The IPC is a crucial component of the Indian legal system, as it establishes the principles and guidelines for determining criminal liability and the appropriate punishments for various offenses. It serves as the primary reference point for law enforcement agencies, prosecutors, and the judiciary in addressing criminal matters within the country.

The code is divided into 23 chapters, each addressing a specific category of offenses, such as offenses against the state, offenses against public tranquility, offenses affecting the human body, and offenses against property. The IPC also includes provisions for the punishment of attempts, abetment, and criminal conspiracy, ensuring a comprehensive approach to addressing criminal behavior.

The Indian Penal Code, 1860 has been amended and updated over the years to address evolving societal needs and emerging criminal trends. These amendments have aimed to strengthen the legal framework, enhance the effectiveness of law enforcement, and ensure the protection of the rights and interests of citizens.

Overall, the Indian Penal Code, 1860 is a foundational component of the Indian legal system, providing the substantive criminal law that governs the administration of justice and the maintenance of law and order in the country.</data>
