      <data key="d0">MAGISTRATE</data>
      <data key="d1">PERSON</data>
      <data key="d2">14.0</data>
      <data key="d5">A Magistrate is a judicial officer who has the authority to perform various legal functions within their local jurisdiction. They are empowered to arrest or order the arrest of an offender, issue warrants and orders, and authorize the custody of accused persons.

Magistrates can issue arrest warrants and orders, allowing them to initiate the arrest of individuals suspected of committing a crime. They can also order a police investigation, even for non-cognizable offenses, which are offenses that do not require an arrest without a warrant.

Furthermore, Magistrates are responsible for extending the police custody and judicial custody of accused persons under Sections 167 of the Code of Criminal Procedure (CrPC) and 187 of the Bombay Nursing Homes and Establishments Act (BNSS). This means they have the authority to determine the length of time an accused individual can be held in custody during the investigation and trial process.

Additionally, Magistrates can authorize the detention of accused persons under the BNSS, which is a law that regulates the operation of nursing homes and other healthcare establishments.

In summary, a Magistrate is a judicial officer who plays a crucial role in the criminal justice system. They have the power to arrest or order the arrest of offenders, issue warrants and orders, initiate police investigations, and authorize the custody and detention of accused persons. This comprehensive authority allows Magistrates to ensure the proper administration of justice within their local jurisdiction.</data>
