      <data key="d0">CRPC</data>
      <data key="d1">ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d2">23.0</data>
      <data key="d5">The CRPC (Code of Criminal Procedure) is the previous criminal procedure code that governed arrests, detention, and bail procedures in India. It was the law that was in place before the introduction of the BNSS (Bail and Norms for Securing Suspects).

The CrPC required that a person in police custody be produced before a Magistrate within 24 hours. This was a key provision that ensured the rights of the accused were protected and that they were not held in custody indefinitely without judicial oversight.

The CrPC was the primary law that regulated the criminal justice system in India, covering aspects such as the powers of the police, the rights of the accused, and the procedures for trials and appeals. It was the previous law that was in place before the introduction of the BNSS, which is now the new criminal procedure code.

While the CrPC and the BNSS share some similarities in their overall purpose of governing criminal procedures, the BNSS is likely to have introduced some changes and updates to the previous system. The summary provided does not go into the specific details of how the BNSS differs from the CrPC, but it is clear that the CrPC was the previous law that was in place before the BNSS was introduced.

In summary, the CRPC (Code of Criminal Procedure) was the previous criminal procedure code that governed arrests, detention, and bail procedures in India. It required that a person in police custody be produced before a Magistrate within 24 hours, and it was the primary law regulating the criminal justice system before the introduction of the BNSS (Bail and Norms for Securing Suspects), which is now the new criminal procedure code.</data>
