    <node id="30">
      <data key="d0">NATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS COMMISSION</data>
      <data key="d1">ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d2">29.0</data>
      <data key="d5">The National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) is a statutory body in India that is responsible for looking into human rights violations in the country. The NHRC has issued various guidelines and directives related to the protection and promotion of human rights.

One of the key areas that the NHRC has focused on is the use of handcuffs during arrests. The NHRC has provided specific guidelines on the use of handcuffs, which are intended to ensure that the rights of individuals are protected during the arrest process. These guidelines are aimed at preventing the misuse or excessive use of handcuffs, which can be a violation of an individual's human rights.

The NHRC's guidelines on the use of handcuffs are in contrast with the provisions of the Bombay Police Act (BNSS), which allows for the use of handcuffs in certain situations. The NHRC has stated that the BNSS provision contravenes the guidelines it has issued on the use of handcuffs, and has called for the BNSS provision to be amended or repealed.

In addition to the guidelines on the use of handcuffs, the NHRC has also issued broader guidelines on arrest procedures. These guidelines are intended to ensure that the rights of individuals are protected during the arrest process, and that the arrest is carried out in a manner that is consistent with the principles of human rights.

The NHRC's role in addressing human rights violations in India is an important one, as it serves as an independent body that can investigate and address complaints of human rights violations. The NHRC's work has been instrumental in bringing attention to various human rights issues in the country and in advocating for the protection and promotion of human rights.

Overall, the National Human Rights Commission plays a crucial role in ensuring that the rights of individuals in India are protected and that any violations of these rights are addressed in a timely and effective manner.</data>
