      <data key="d0">CODE OF CRIMINAL PROCEDURE</data>
      <data key="d1">ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d2">29.0</data>
      <data key="d5">The Code of Criminal Procedure (CrPC) is the previous criminal law code in India that the proposed Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita (BNS) and Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita (BNSS) seek to modify and improve upon. It is a law in India that governs criminal procedure, including provisions such as Section 167.

The CrPC was the primary criminal procedure code in India before being proposed to be replaced by the BNS and BNSS. These new legislative proposals aim to update and enhance the existing criminal justice system in the country.

The CrPC contains the rules and regulations that govern the process of criminal investigations, trials, and the administration of criminal justice in India. It outlines the powers and duties of police officers, magistrates, and other authorities involved in the criminal justice system.

The proposed BNS and BNSS aim to build upon the foundation of the CrPC, incorporating feedback and lessons learned to create a more comprehensive and effective criminal justice framework for India. The new legislation is expected to streamline procedures, enhance due process protections, and align the system more closely with contemporary needs and international best practices.

By replacing the CrPC with the BNS and BNSS, the Indian government seeks to modernize the criminal justice system, improve efficiency, and ensure greater fairness and accountability in the administration of criminal law. The new codes are expected to address any shortcomings or contradictions present in the existing CrPC, providing a more coherent and effective approach to criminal procedure in the country.

Overall, the Code of Criminal Procedure has been a foundational element of India's criminal justice system, and the proposed BNS and BNSS represent an effort to build upon this foundation and create a more robust and responsive legal framework for addressing criminal matters in the country.</data>
