      <data key="d0">CONSTITUTION OF INDIA</data>
      <data key="d1">ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d2">27.0</data>
      <data key="d5">The Constitution of India is the supreme law of the country. It establishes the framework of the government, defines its powers and duties, and protects the fundamental rights of the citizens.

The Constitution of India, particularly Articles 21 and 22, guarantees protection to individuals against arbitrary arrest and detention, emphasizing the principles of due process and personal liberty. Article 21 states that "No person shall be deprived of his life or personal liberty except according to the procedure established by law." This provision ensures that the government cannot deprive an individual of their life or liberty without following the proper legal procedures.

Furthermore, Article 22 of the Constitution provides additional safeguards against arbitrary arrest and detention. It states that every person who is arrested must be informed of the grounds of their arrest and must be allowed to consult a lawyer of their choice. The article also requires that the arrested person be produced before a magistrate within 24 hours of their arrest, and that they cannot be detained in custody beyond this period without the order of the magistrate.

These constitutional provisions are crucial in protecting the fundamental rights of the citizens and ensuring that the government does not abuse its power. They serve as a check on the government's authority and help maintain the rule of law in the country.

Overall, the Constitution of India is a comprehensive document that not only establishes the structure of the government but also safeguards the rights and liberties of the people. Its emphasis on due process and personal liberty is a testament to the framers' commitment to creating a just and equitable society.</data>
