      <data key="d1">ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d2">54.0</data>
      <data key="d5">Articles 21 and 22 of the Constitution of India are two important provisions that protect the fundamental rights of Indian citizens. These articles are crucial in safeguarding the right to life and personal liberty.

Article 21 of the Indian Constitution states that "No person shall be deprived of his life or personal liberty except according to the procedure established by law." This article ensures that the government cannot arbitrarily deprive an individual of their life or personal liberty without following the due process of law. It has been interpreted by the Supreme Court to include a wide range of rights, such as the right to live with dignity, the right to privacy, the right to clean environment, and the right to free legal aid, among others.

Article 22 of the Indian Constitution deals with the protection against arrest and detention in certain cases. It provides that no person who is arrested shall be detained in custody without being informed of the grounds of such arrest, nor shall they be denied the right to consult and be defended by a legal practitioner of their choice. Article 22 also grants certain safeguards to individuals who are arrested or detained, such as the right to be produced before a magistrate within 24 hours of the arrest and the right to be released on bail, unless there are reasonable grounds to believe that the release would be prejudicial to the public interest.

Together, Articles 21 and 22 form the cornerstone of the fundamental rights guaranteed by the Indian Constitution. They protect the basic human rights of individuals and ensure that the government cannot arbitrarily deprive them of their life and personal liberty. These articles have been interpreted and expanded by the Supreme Court over the years, making them an essential part of the Indian legal framework.</data>
