      <data key="d0">POLICE OFFICER</data>
      <data key="d1">PERSON</data>
      <data key="d2">44.0</data>
      <data key="d5">A police officer is a law enforcement officer who has the authority to make arrests and enforce the law. They are responsible for responding to reports of crimes, investigating incidents, and apprehending individuals who have committed criminal offenses.

Police officers have the power to arrest a person, even for a non-cognizable offense, if the individual refuses to provide their true name and residence. They are also authorized to execute arrest warrants and must inform the arrested person of the particulars of the offense and their right to bail.

When a cognizable offense is reported, police officers are responsible for registering a First Information Report (FIR) and initiating the investigative process. They have the authority to use necessary means to effect an arrest, ensuring the safety of both the officer and the individual being apprehended.

The role of a police officer is multifaceted, as they are tasked with maintaining public order, preventing and detecting crimes, and protecting the rights and safety of citizens. They are expected to act with professionalism, integrity, and respect for the law, while also being mindful of the rights and civil liberties of the individuals they encounter.

In summary, a police officer is a law enforcement official who has the power to arrest individuals, execute warrants, and register FIRs when a cognizable offense is reported. They are responsible for upholding the law and ensuring the safety and security of the community they serve.</data>
