    <node id="159">
      <data key="d0">SECTION 35</data>
      <data key="d1">ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d2">44.0</data>
      <data key="d5">Section 35 of the Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita (BNSS) outlines the specific circumstances in which a police officer may arrest a person without a warrant. This section of the BNSS, which is the legal code governing civil security in the country, provides the legal framework for such arrests.

According to the descriptions provided, Section 35 of the BNSS governs the arrest of a person without a warrant. It specifies the conditions under which a police officer can apprehend an individual without first obtaining a warrant from a judicial authority. This is an important provision in the law, as it allows law enforcement to respond quickly to certain situations where a warrant may not be immediately available, but prompt action is necessary to maintain public order and safety.

The descriptions do not provide any further details about the specific circumstances outlined in Section 35 that would justify an arrest without a warrant. However, it can be inferred that this section of the BNSS is intended to balance the need for effective law enforcement with the protection of individual rights and due process. The law likely outlines a set of clear criteria and procedures that police officers must follow when making such arrests, in order to prevent abuse of this power.

Overall, Section 35 of the BNSS plays a crucial role in the legal framework governing law enforcement and the rights of citizens in the country. By providing the conditions under which a warrantless arrest can be made, it helps to ensure that the police can respond quickly to urgent situations, while also safeguarding the fundamental rights of individuals. This section of the law is an important component of the broader system of civil security and justice in the country.</data>
    </node>
