    <node id="164">
      <data key="d0">PROCLAIMED OFFENDER</data>
      <data key="d1">PERSON</data>
      <data key="d2">44.0</data>
      <data key="d5">A proclaimed offender is an individual who has been declared as such by a court. According to Section 35(1)(b) of the Bombay Police Act, a proclaimed offender is someone who can be arrested by the police without a warrant.

The process of being declared a proclaimed offender typically occurs when an individual is accused of a crime and evades arrest or fails to appear in court. The court then issues a proclamation, declaring the person a proclaimed offender. This designation allows the police to apprehend the individual without the need for a warrant, as they are considered to be actively evading the law.

The purpose of this legal status is to facilitate the arrest and prosecution of individuals who are attempting to avoid the judicial process. By being declared a proclaimed offender, the individual loses certain rights and protections that would normally be afforded to a citizen, making it easier for law enforcement to locate and detain them.

Once an individual has been declared a proclaimed offender, they may face additional legal consequences, such as the seizure of their property or the suspension of their passport. The proclaimed offender status remains in effect until the individual is either arrested and brought before the court, or the court decides to revoke the proclamation.

It is important to note that the designation of "proclaimed offender" is a serious legal status, and it is typically only applied in cases where the individual is believed to be actively evading the law. The decision to declare someone a proclaimed offender is made by the court, and it is not a decision that is taken lightly.</data>
    </node>
