    <edge id="e28" source="28" target="29">
      <data key="d3">25.0</data>
      <data key="d4">Criminal Procedure)...</data>
      <data key="d6">The CRPC (Code of Criminal Procedure) and the BNSS (Bail and Narcotic Substances Seizure) are two related legal frameworks in the country. The BNSS contains additional regulations around arrests that supplement the CRPC, making changes and expansions to the rules around arrests and detention that were previously covered under the CRPC.

The BNSS has modified and expanded upon the detention and bail provisions in the previous CRPC law. It retains the provision from the CRPC to produce a person in police custody before a Magistrate within 24 hours. However, the BNSS has introduced new regulations and procedures that go beyond what was covered in the CRPC.

The key changes introduced by the BNSS include:

1. Expanded arrest powers: The BNSS grants law enforcement additional powers to arrest individuals suspected of involvement in narcotic-related offenses, going beyond the arrest provisions in the CRPC.

2. Stricter detention rules: The BNSS has put in place more stringent rules around the detention of individuals, including longer permissible detention periods and additional requirements for producing suspects before a Magistrate.

3. Bail restrictions: The BNSS has modified the bail provisions, making it more difficult for individuals accused of narcotic-related crimes to be granted bail, compared to the previous CRPC framework.

4. Seizure of assets: The BNSS empowers law enforcement to seize assets and property of individuals suspected of involvement in narcotic-related activities, even before they are convicted.

Overall, the BNSS represents a significant expansion and strengthening of the legal framework around narcotic-related crimes, building upon and going beyond the provisions of the CRPC. While the BNSS retains some core elements of the CRPC, such as the requirement to produce a suspect before a Magistrate within 24 hours, it has introduced a range of new regulations and procedures that give law enforcement greater powers and impose stricter conditions on suspects.</data>
    </edge>
