      <data key="d6">SECTION 41 of the BHARATIYA NAGARIK SURAKSHA SANHITA (BNSS) grants Executive and Judicial Magistrates the power to arrest or order the arrest of an accused person. Specifically, Section 41(2) of the BNSS empowers Magistrates to arrest or direct the arrest of any person within their jurisdiction.

The BNSS is a comprehensive legal framework that outlines the rights and responsibilities of citizens, as well as the powers and duties of law enforcement and judicial authorities. Section 41 of the BNSS is a crucial provision that enables Magistrates to take necessary action to maintain law and order and ensure the safety of the public.

Through the authority granted by Section 41, Magistrates can arrest or direct the arrest of individuals who are suspected of committing a crime or pose a threat to public safety. This power is an essential tool for Magistrates to effectively carry out their duties and uphold the rule of law.

The descriptions provided indicate that the provisions of Section 41 are consistent and do not contain any contradictions. Both descriptions highlight the Magistrates' ability to arrest or order the arrest of individuals, emphasizing the importance of this legal provision in the BNSS.

In summary, SECTION 41 of the BHARATIYA NAGARIK SURAKSHA SANHITA (BNSS) grants Executive and Judicial Magistrates the power to arrest or order the arrest of an accused person, including the ability to arrest or direct the arrest of any person within their jurisdiction. This provision is a crucial component of the BNSS, enabling Magistrates to maintain law and order and ensure the safety of the public.</data>
